article.headline: SE Louisiana 76, Southern 71
article.story: HAMMOND, La. (AP) -- Amir Abdur-Rahim scored 23 points as Southeastern Louisiana overcame poor shooting in the first half to defeat Southern 76-71 on Saturday. The Lions (3-2) shot just 26.9 percent from the floor in the first half, but thanks to 11-of-13 shooting from the foul line, trailed the Jaguars (2-3) 29-27 at halftime. A 3-pointer by Abdur-Rahim with 14:13 left put SLU back on top 43-42. The Lions built the lead to as much as 52-44 with 10:38 left on a pair of free throws by Terry West. Southern tied the game at 60-60 with 4:57 left on a jumper by Peter Cipriano and regained the lead when Trayvean Scott hit a 3-pointer with 3:59 remaining. The game stayed within one point until Abdur-Rahim scored the Lions' final eight points, first a 3-pointer with 1:06 left and then five free throws in the final minute. West was 10-of-11 from the free throw line and scored 19 points. Jonathan Patton added 13 for the Lions, who shot 51.7 percent from the field in the second half. Scott, who was 5-of-11 from 3-point range, scored 17 points to lead Southern. Jerimie Collier added 12 and three others -- Jarvis Vaughn, Nick Egland and Cipriano -- had 10 each.
